chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Abortion laws should be written to minimize preventable harm while respecting that citizens hold sincere, differing views about fetal moral status. Policy can protect confidential, timely care early in pregnancy and guarantee clear, non-negotiable exceptions for life-threatening emergencies, serious health threats, rape, incest, and nonviable or catastrophic fetal diagnoses, while setting any later limits in objective terms that clinicians can apply without fear of prosecution. Whatever the boundaries, lawmakers should pair them with proven measures—affordable contraception, accurate sex education, prenatal and postpartum care, and practical supports for parenting and adoption—so fewer pregnancies end in crisis.
